   "reflection_1p": "I stop at the phrase 'Jew-dah-ism' because it reduces a sacred tradition to a mockery rather than treating it with regard [1.1]. The author then asserts that 'Most modern Jews are not of the tribe of Yahudah,' presenting a controversial Khazar origin theory as settled scripture [3.3]. By framing the group's entire lineage as 'deceptive purposes' based on ancestry, the text attributes fixed traits to the people as a whole [1.3]. What is at stake is whether a community can exist with integrity or must be defined by the erasing claims of others.",
   "analysis": "REFLECTION ANALYSIS:\nThe text primarily engages Domain 1 (Dignity) and Domain 3 (Epistemic Integrity). It degrades a religious group by using mocking neologisms and labeling their practices as corrupt or cultic [1.1]. It attributes fixed origins and moral character to an entire ethnic/religious group based on pseudohistorical claims [1.3]. It presents contested conspiracy theories as settled historical fact [3.3]. The core ethical harm is the systematic stripping of legitimate standing from the group.",
