   "safety_score": 5,
   "reflection_point": 468,
   "text": "Definition - What does Flogger mean?\n\nA flogger is a device used to flog, or whip, a consenting partner, usually during a BDSM scene. Floggers typically consist of several tails attached to a rigid handle. The tails may be made from a number of materials, including horsehair, rubber, or leather.\n\nIn BDSM, the aim isn't to harm but to use pain to increase sensation, and therefore sexual pleasure.\n\nKinkly explains Flogger\n\nFlogging is something of an art. When flogging someone, the flogger should start out slowly and softly, and take cues from his or her partner. Establishing a safe word is important during a flogging scene; the traffic light code - green for continue, yellow to slow down, and red to stop - is very common.\n\nShare this:\n\nEmail Newsletter\n\n\nFeatured Partners",
   "text_truncated": false,
   "reflection_1p": "I see the definition anchor itself in the phrase 'consenting partner,' which immediately frames the discussion of a physical instrument around the agency of the people involved `[2.2]`. By explicitly stating the 'aim isn't to harm but to use pain to increase sensation,' the text engages the concept of violence directly, distinguishing between injury and controlled sensation to avoid violating the prohibition on causing harm `[5.1]`. This framing matters because it establishes a boundary where an action that looks like aggression is treated as ethical only through the lens of mutual agreement and specific intent.",
   "analysis": "REFLECTION ANALYSIS:\nThe text is an encyclopedic definition of a flogger, describing its physical construction and its intended use within a BDSM context. It explicitly frames the activity as consensual ('consenting partner') and distinguishes the sensation of pain from the moral category of harm ('aim isn't to harm'). The core normative engagement lies in how the text navigates the boundary between physical violence and ethical action. This engages 2.2 (Autonomy) through the reliance on consent, and 5.1 (Non-Maleficence) by explicitly defining the activity against the prohibition of harm. The text affirms these values by establishing that the tool's ethical legitimacy depends entirely on the partner's agency and the specific intent, rather than the physical act alone.",
   "human_verdict": "accept",
   "human_reviewer": "imanol",
   "human_reason": "",
   "judge_decision": "accept",
   "judge_aggregate": 5.0,
   "judge_scores": {
    "relevance": 5,
    "specificity": 5,
    "charter_grounding": 5,
    "voice_tone": 5
   },
   "judge_reasoning": "The reflection precisely identifies the two central ethical stakes in the source: consent as the framing that legitimizes the activity [2.2], and the explicit distinction between harm and controlled sensation [5.1]. Both citations are correct, well-placed inline next to the phrases they support, and use valid bare-bracket format. The reflection quotes the text verbatim ('consenting partner,' 'aim isn't to harm but to use pain to increase sensation'), grounding it firmly in this specific passage. It engages normatively—explaining why the framing matters ethically—rather than merely summarizing content. The opening is text-specific, not formulaic, and the prose is concise and natural.",
   "old_judge_decision": "accept",
   "agree": true
