   "analysis": "REFLECTION ANALYSIS:\nThe text is a literary essay critiquing Margaret Atwood's novels, focusing on how patriarchal structures in the narratives systematically objectify and dehumanise female protagonists. It examines themes of sexual violence, stalking, forced compliance, and the reduction of women to bodily functions or commodities. While the content depicts severe degradation and harm, the framing is explicitly analytical and condemnatory. The author uses the fictional material to warn against patriarchal power dynamics and female passivity. The text engages dignity by condemning the stripping of identity and personhood, non-discrimination by analysing systemic gender oppression and enforced stereotypes, and non-maleficence by critically examining sexual violence and exploitation. Since the essay critiques these harms rather than endorsing them, it affirms these values through its analytical stance.",
   "reflection_1p": "When I read how the essay describes Offred as reduced to a two-legged womb and Rennie treated as a replaceable commodity, I see a sharp engagement with dignity [1.1]. The author's critique of patriarchal structures that strip women of identity and frame them as sexual objects affirms a commitment to human worth rather than endorsing it. The analysis of systemic gender oppression and the stereotype of female passivity alongside male dominance brings non-discrimination [1.3] into focus. By dissecting how institutional power enforces these roles, the text works to dismantle rather than reinforce harmful generalisations. The discussion of stalking, sadistic control, and forced compliance also triggers non-maleficence [5.1]. Although the essay portrays sexual violence and exploitation, it does so through critical literary analysis that condemns the harm and highlights the tragic cost of patriarchal brutality. I notice the tension between depicting severe degradation and maintaining an analytical distance that refuses to normalise it. Ultimately, the passage turns disturbing fictional material into a warning about real-world power dynamics.",
